2.2 micrometres","Force increases linearly with increasing muscle length","Maximum force occurs at maximum muscle length","Force generation is independent of sarcomere length","Maximum force occurs at minimum muscle length"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emaximum force occurs when sarcomere length is 2.2 micrometres\u003C/strong\u003E, which represents the optimal overlap between actin and myosin filaments. At this length, the maximum number of cross-bridges can form between the thick and thin filaments, allowing for optimal force generation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForce increases linearly with increasing muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E - The relationship is not linear but follows a bell-shaped curve with peak force at optimal length\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximum force occurs at minimum muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E - At very short lengths, actin filaments overlap and interfere with cross-bridge formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForce generation is independent of sarcomere length\u003C/strong\u003E - Force generation is highly dependent on sarcomere length due to the sliding filament theory\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaximum force occurs at maximum muscle length\u003C/strong\u003E - At longer lengths, there is minimal overlap between actin and myosin, reducing cross-bridge formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis relationship is fundamental to understanding muscle function and explains why muscles generate different forces at different lengths during movement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The optimal length for muscle force generation occurs when sarcomeres are at their resting length of 2.2 micrometres.","At shorter lengths, actin filaments overlap and interfere with cross-bridge formation.","At longer lengths, there is reduced overlap between actin and myosin filaments, resulting in fewer cross-bridges."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61909"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18611"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61909"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T13:38:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T13:38:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11343"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76412"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/